        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Calendar Overview",
            Slug = "calendar-overview",
            Summary = "What the Calendar module shows, how the three views work, how PO deliveries integrate, and how it connects to jobs.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/calendar"]""",
            Tags = """["calendar","scheduling","jobs"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Calendar Overview\n\nThe Calendar gives you a visual timeline of your jobs by their due dates, plus optional delivery dates for purchase orders. Use it to see what is coming up, what is overdue, and how work is spread across the days, weeks, and months ahead.\n\n### Three Views\n\nThe calendar has three views — **Month**, **Week**, and **Day** — that you switch with buttons at the top. Each view shows the same work at a different level of detail.\n\n- **Month** shows a traditional grid. Each day shows its date, up to three job labels, and a count of any that don't fit. Job labels are colored by stage and flag Critical and High priority work.\n- **Week** shows seven days side by side with larger job labels that also include the customer name. It's handy for planning the current or coming week.\n- **Day** is a list for a single date. Each job shows its full detail: number, title, priority, customer, stage, and who it's assigned to. A day with nothing scheduled shows a friendly empty message.\n\n### Show or Hide PO Deliveries\n\nAt the top there's a button to turn purchase order deliveries on or off. When it's on, expected delivery dates appear on the calendar next to your jobs. Each delivery shows its PO number, the vendor, and how many lines it has. This helps you plan production around incoming materials.\n\n### How Jobs Appear\n\nEach job label shows:\n- Its **number** and **title**\n- A **colored left edge** that matches its current stage\n- A **priority flag** for Critical or High priority work\n- An **overdue warning** when the due date has passed\n\n### Filter by Track\n\nA menu at the top lets you show only jobs from one track. This is handy when you run several tracks (Production, R&D, Maintenance) and want to focus on one.\n\n### Opening a Job\n\nThe calendar is a view-only timeline — you can't edit a job here. To work on a job, **click it** in any view. The calendar takes you to the Kanban board with that job already open, where you can change its stage, edit details, log time, and more. It's a fast way to spot a due date and jump straight to the work. Delivery labels are for reference only and don't open anything.\n\n### Moving Around\n\nUse the back and forward arrows to move by one month, week, or day, depending on your view. The **Today** button jumps you back to the current date. Clicking an empty day (not a job) in Month or Week view opens Day view for that date.\n\n### When to Use the Calendar\n\n- To see the week ahead and spot scheduling conflicts\n- To check which jobs are overdue at a glance\n- To line up delivery dates with your production plan\n- To jump to a specific day and review everything due\n- To filter by track and focus on one part of the business","sections":[]}"""
