        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Calendar, Events & Working Days — Reference",
            Slug = "calendar-reference",
            Summary = "The deeper how-to for planners: making the most of Show PO Deliveries, why a job may not appear, running events and meetings, and how Working Calendars set your business days.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/calendar"]""",
            Tags = """["calendar","reference"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Getting the Most from Show PO Deliveries\n\nShow PO Deliveries is **your own choice** — the calendar remembers whether you left it on or off and brings it back the way you had it next time you open the page. It starts off, so turn it on the first time you want to plan around incoming materials.\n\nWhen it's on, the deliveries you see always match the days on screen. Page forward to next month and you'll see that month's expected deliveries; page back and you'll see the earlier ones. Use this to line up a delivery date with the job that's waiting on it — if the metal lands Tuesday, don't promise the part Monday. Turn deliveries off again when you just want a clean view of what's due.\n\n## Why a Job Might Not Appear\n\nA job shows up on the calendar on its **due date**. That means two things worth knowing:\n\n- **A job with no due date won't appear at all.** If you expect a job on the calendar and can't find it, open it on the board and check that it has a due date set. Deliveries work the same way — they land on their expected delivery date.\n- **Archived jobs drop off.** Only active work shows. Once a job is archived, it leaves the calendar, which keeps the view about what's still ahead of you.\n\nIn Month view each day shows the first **3** jobs and a '+N more' note for the rest — open the day, or switch to Week or Day view, to see every job. If a busy shop makes the month look crowded, use the **track filter** to narrow to one line of business, or work in Week view where nothing is hidden.\n\n## Running Events & Meetings\n\nEvents are a **separate tool from the job calendar** — production meetings, training sessions, safety stand-downs, and the like. They're available when your site uses the employees feature. Anyone signed in can see events and the upcoming-events list; managers and admins are the ones who create, change, or cancel them. If you're invited, you can accept or decline your own invitation.\n\nEach event has a start and end time, a title, an optional description and location, and a type — **Meeting, Training, Safety, or Other** — so people can tell a toolbox talk from a training class at a glance. When you set one up, invitees get an invitation right away, and the app sends a reminder before it starts so nobody misses it. If you decline, the reminders stop. Mark an event required when attendance isn't optional — the reminder for those carries a stronger warning tone.\n\n## Where Events Show Up\n\nThe calendar page shows **only jobs and PO deliveries** — events don't appear there. You create and manage events in one place, the **Events panel in Admin**, and everyone else sees them, view-only, where they'll actually notice: on the shop-floor display, on the Events tab of a person's profile, in the upcoming-events list, and as reminders and notifications. Outside the Admin panel you can view an event and respond to your invite, but not edit it.\n\n## Working Calendars vs the Calendar Page\n\nDon't confuse the Calendar page with **Working Calendars**, a separate admin setup (admins only). The Calendar page shows *your work* — jobs and deliveries. Working Calendars define *your business days*: your time zone, which days of the week you're open, your holidays (including the day each is observed), and your shifts. Setting these correctly matters to everyone, because they're what the app uses to count real working days — so a vendor lead time, a material plan, or a deadline skips your weekends and holidays instead of promising a part on a day you're closed. The rules apply to the whole company by default, and any location that keeps different hours can set its own. One calendar is marked the default.","sections":[]}"""
